yes you'll have to learn the actual characters.  As far as &quot;romanisation&quot; there isn't really much to learn, it's just the sounds of the language written in our letters.  <br>
<br>
you can use a pen/pencil/brush/crayon/whatever you desire <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  to write japanese.  But I would suggest you use something with a fine point, it will make it easier to write some of the more intricate kanji, and will allow you to write kanji readings/grammer notes in the margins when you begin to read your textbook.<br>
<br>
which brings us to...... a textbook!  you'll need one (actually several) ones of these for sure.  there are countless beginner textbooks out there, and knowing which one is a &quot;good&quot; one is a matter of personal preferance and luck.  There is a fairly recent thread below (i forget the name but it has something like 42 posts) which goes on in some detail about the trials and tribulations of choosing a textbook.  <br>
<br>
the flash cards are a great idea, both for learning the basic letters and then moving on to grammer patterns, etc.  As far as I'm concerned there is nothing in the world that can't be learned by flashcards <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   Okay okay... I'm just teasing.  I just like feeling like I'm &quot;studying&quot; by carrying them around everywhere.  But anyhow, flashcards = good thing. (too much martha stewart)<br>
<br>
You'll need a teacher.  Or a japanese speaking friend or a penpal or something.  <br>
<br>
&gt;so I can speak it rather well in that when I go to japan in about 2.5 years I can talk and not be troubled<br>
<br>
sadly, i've been studying for a few years now, and I still find myself troubled when i go to japan. but that's usually because somebody has nicked my tonkatsu while i wasn't looking and I have to regulate.  (uhhh... sorrry.... *maimai has gone crazy*)<br>
<br>
anyway, all joking aside, learning japanese &quot;rather well&quot; in 2.5 years by yourself is a tall order.  So you'll have to study hard, practice everyday and with some luck, and lots of perseverance you'll find you can probably reach a level where you can communicate essential ideas and carry out basic conversations by then.  It will help you exponentially if you were to take some classes/find a teacher.  <br>
